1. Navigation & Inspection
Use these to "orient" yourself within the Linux filesystem.

pwd: Present Working Directory. Run this to see exactly where you are in the folder hierarchy.

ls: List files and folders.

ls -l: List files with detailed information (permissions, size, owner).

history: Shows a list of all commands you have typed in this session (perfect for proof of work).



2. File & Directory Operations
The core "building blocks" of managing a server.

mkdir <folder_name>: Create a new directory (e.g., mkdir Day1-Practice).

cd <folder_name>: Move into that directory.

touch <file_name>: Create an empty file (e.g., touch myscript.sh).

cat <file_name>: View the contents of a file in the terminal.

rm -r <folder_name>: Delete a directory and its contents (Use with caution!).



3. System Health & Resources
DevOps engineers use these to monitor server performance.

df -h: Check disk space usage in a "human-readable" format (GB/MB).

top: Displays real-time CPU, RAM, and process usage. This is your "Task Manager" in the terminal.



4. Permission Logic (The Math)
This is a key part of your notes. Practice assigning specific permissions:

The Values: Read (4), Write (2), Execute (1).

chmod 777 <file>: Full access for everyone (4+2+1 for User, Group, and Others).

Try this practice:

chmod 700 <file>: Only the User can read/write/execute.

chmod 644 <file>: User can read/write; others can only read.



